1
00:00:00,993 --> 00:00:19,896
Namo tassa bhagavato harhato sambha sambhudassa Namo tassa bhagavato harhato sambha sambhudassa

2
00:00:19,876 --> 00:00:28,929
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa.

3
00:00:30,091 --> 00:00:34,618
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

4
00:00:40,167 --> 00:00:42,491
So, I thought I'd tackle this...

5
00:00:43,787 --> 00:00:45,170
The problem of free will.

6
00:00:45,231 --> 00:00:49,618
How does that come up in the Buddha's teaching?

7
00:00:49,637 --> 00:00:52,362
Free will.

8
00:00:52,383 --> 00:00:56,930
Well, this idea of free will has been with us for a heck of a long time.

9
00:00:58,453 --> 00:01:07,989
You know, even going back, were we at the mercy of the gods or could we instruct the gods to do things for us?

10
00:01:09,201 --> 00:01:27,171
So in terms of polytheism, that's how it began, you know, this idea that there was some controlling deity or deities, and the idea was to get them on your side, sympathetic magic, things like that.

11
00:01:27,673 --> 00:01:30,417
And then

12
00:01:30,397 --> 00:01:38,609
Somehow it corrupted into the idea that if you actually did the ritual perfectly, you could then control.

13
00:01:38,629 --> 00:01:40,373
And that was when the Buddha appeared.

14
00:01:41,274 --> 00:01:54,936
So the Brahmins there, who control the whole business of sacrifice, they knew the specific words, nobody else could learn them, and they knew the specific action, exactly what to do, and this would bring about the desired results, you see.

15
00:01:56,688 --> 00:02:01,873
So there's some sort of free will thrown in there with some sense of control.

16
00:02:01,933 --> 00:02:03,096
That's what we want, isn't it?

17
00:02:03,396 --> 00:02:03,977
Control.

18
00:02:03,996 --> 00:02:12,106
I think in the West we've sort of cornered ourselves into a very sharp individualism.

19
00:02:13,087 --> 00:02:17,854
We don't really see ourselves too much as social beings, as social will.

20
00:02:17,873 --> 00:02:24,282
We tend to see ourselves as very little individual pods who demand to do what we want to do.

21
00:02:24,262 --> 00:02:31,397
So the idea of free will, especially from the Enlightenment, is something that's core stuff for us.

22
00:02:32,460 --> 00:02:39,435
And it comes out, as you'll see when I talk later, in capitalism, the idea of freedom, freedom of choice, all that sort of stuff.

23
00:02:42,031 --> 00:02:51,983
The other thing is that with the Enlightenment, that's ours, 18th century, which I totally believe in, you know, the idea of rational.

24
00:02:52,264 --> 00:03:03,056
So free will is to do with something about thinking about it and about coming to some sort of philosophical conclusion that we have or we don't have free will.

25
00:03:03,698 --> 00:03:11,768
But there's a very interesting discourse here, or at least there's a part that really interests me, from the Buddhists, the opening discourse, actually the longer...

26
00:03:11,747 --> 00:03:37,300
of the longer discourses and he lists quite a huge amount I think 64 different speculative views some of them you'll have heard of whether the cosmos was infinite or finite whether the enlightened person was born or died or what not and everybody has a view on these things and this is what he says he says all such views

27
00:03:37,280 --> 00:03:45,923
are merely the feeling of those who do not know and see, the worry and uncertainty of those immersed in craving.

28
00:03:47,346 --> 00:03:51,036
And what catches my attention is merely the feeling.

29
00:03:53,024 --> 00:03:59,512
See, we tend to be up here, and if we can work something out logically, it sort of separates out from feeling.

30
00:03:59,532 --> 00:04:13,508
Therefore you believe in free will, whether you actually feel it or not, or rather you discard feeling, you push it away, on the understanding that there is free will.

31
00:04:14,449 --> 00:04:15,890
Yeah?

32
00:04:16,471 --> 00:04:22,879
Even if I don't feel free, so long as I say to myself I am free, I go around thinking that I am free.

33
00:04:25,980 --> 00:04:26,843
I don't know if that makes sense.

34
00:04:28,646 --> 00:04:32,737
Hopefully, as we go on, it will get more obvious.

35
00:04:33,980 --> 00:04:42,100
If we take another discourse, which the Buddha actually called his honey bowl discourse, it's a delicious sweet you can still buy in India.

36
00:04:42,737 --> 00:04:49,024
And he gave a cryptic teaching there, and all these monks who were listening to him didn't ask him anything about it.

37
00:04:49,043 --> 00:04:54,449
They went off to this other monk called Mahākaccāna, who was very good at expounding the short teachings of the Buddha.

38
00:04:55,110 --> 00:04:58,112
So they ask him, and he says to them, why don't you ask him?

39
00:04:58,413 --> 00:05:00,134
And they go right there.

40
00:05:00,154 --> 00:05:01,076
They say, well, whatever.

41
00:05:01,536 --> 00:05:06,761
So he gives them the longer teaching, and then they go back to the Buddha and say, this is what Mahākaccāna said.

42
00:05:07,581 --> 00:05:08,682
It's funny, isn't it?

43
00:05:08,702 --> 00:05:12,627
And the Buddha says, well, if you'd have asked me, I would have said the same thing.

44
00:05:12,607 --> 00:05:18,088
Sort of a roundabout way of getting there, you know.

45
00:05:18,711 --> 00:05:20,980
Anyway, the core of it is this.

46
00:05:22,764 --> 00:05:26,430
What we counter-know is dependent on contact.

47
00:05:27,971 --> 00:05:30,814
That's the part of the Wheel of Dependent Origination, contact.

48
00:05:31,696 --> 00:05:38,303
So if it's something that's visual, there's got to be contact at the visual base, the retina.

49
00:05:39,105 --> 00:05:42,850
But remember there's also the sixth sense in Buddhism, which is emotion, thought.

50
00:05:42,829 --> 00:05:48,398
So something must arise into the mind to make contact, your stimulus.

51
00:05:49,278 --> 00:05:51,040
So that's, for instance, when you wake up in the morning.

52
00:05:51,482 --> 00:05:54,786
The first thing that comes up, you don't beckon it, it just arises.

53
00:05:55,648 --> 00:06:03,298
So much of our day is just stuff arising, either coming from an outside stimulus or from something inside us.

54
00:06:05,180 --> 00:06:06,642
And then he says...

55
00:06:07,923 --> 00:06:15,088
That upon this, feelings arise, feelings and perceptions.

56
00:06:15,148 --> 00:06:20,024
Now, in Buddhist psychology, feeling and perception arises at the same time.

57
00:06:21,052 --> 00:06:31,055
And all a feeling is, is a distinguishing in the mind between what is experienced as pleasant or unpleasant.

58
00:06:31,076 --> 00:06:32,098
And that's your perception.

59
00:06:32,740 --> 00:06:38,875
So whatever feeling arises, as it arises, it's always experienced as neutral.

60
00:06:40,103 --> 00:06:46,353
But as soon as you flip into a perception of it, it immediately cuts the world up into likeable, unlikable.

61
00:06:47,615 --> 00:06:57,372
So, for instance, in your meditation, you might find some emotion arising, which you describe or which you label as, or at least your attitude towards it is unlikable.

62
00:06:57,853 --> 00:06:59,175
It's a bit of depression or something.

63
00:06:59,745 --> 00:07:19,036
Now, if you, as it were, take your attention away from the emotional value of it to the sensation value of it in the body, and you get down to just thick feelings or those funny feelings that come up with depression, whatever, heat, whatever it is,

64
00:07:19,016 --> 00:07:28,658
then you'll see as you move towards that base, the idea of like and dislike begin to fade out a bit, until you can get to a point where there's just sensation.

65
00:07:29,259 --> 00:07:32,406
And at that point, you're at the point where the stimulus comes in.

66
00:07:33,108 --> 00:07:34,512
So you've gone back on it, you see.

67
00:07:37,293 --> 00:07:43,139
When you do something like that, you begin to realize that it's our definition of things.

68
00:07:44,180 --> 00:07:49,305
It's our definition of things which is the core problem, because it comes from our view, our view of something.

69
00:07:49,906 --> 00:07:56,394
So, for instance, if we're conditioned to be racist, as soon as we see somebody of another race, unpleasant feelings arise.

70
00:07:57,754 --> 00:07:58,755
It'll just happen naturally.

71
00:07:58,795 --> 00:08:00,617
If you're not conditioned that way, it doesn't arise.

72
00:08:01,499 --> 00:08:05,764
So these feelings that we get are also based on our views and opinions.

73
00:08:07,009 --> 00:08:11,473
And they arise with feeling.

74
00:08:12,095 --> 00:08:14,117
So the heart-mind work in unison.

75
00:08:15,677 --> 00:08:17,800
It's we in the West that have split these two up.

76
00:08:18,081 --> 00:08:32,595
You know, if you go East, for instance, to Thailand, when they say, I can't remember what their word is for mind, something like chitta or something, you'll see they're not actually talking about, they're not pointing to the head, they're pointing to the heart.

77
00:08:35,292 --> 00:08:43,524
Then he says, as soon as we perceive something, we'll start thinking about it, and then you get that proliferation.

78
00:08:43,543 --> 00:08:47,169
So now, at the root of this feeling perception is the me.

79
00:08:48,731 --> 00:08:50,914
That self-awareness.

80
00:08:50,934 --> 00:09:03,113
When you're in meditation and you get that very strong feeling of being an observer, you've distanced, shall we say, so much away from your body, your feelings, your sensations, that you get this feeling of the watcher.

81
00:09:03,413 --> 00:09:03,693
Yeah?

82
00:09:03,714 --> 00:09:03,813
Yeah?

83
00:09:04,537 --> 00:09:06,059
So, you know, turn on that.

84
00:09:06,240 --> 00:09:07,842
Where's that coming from?

85
00:09:07,863 --> 00:09:10,187
If you're aware of the watcher, you can't be the watcher.

86
00:09:12,190 --> 00:09:14,554
As soon as you make something an object, you can't be it.

87
00:09:15,996 --> 00:09:26,274
So, if you're observing and there's that feeling of watching, of a watcher, just shift your attention and try and catch where that feeling's arising from.

88
00:09:29,326 --> 00:09:32,369
So now, as it's most deluded, this me thinks it's this body and mind.

89
00:09:32,408 --> 00:09:34,129
And what's its purpose?

90
00:09:34,190 --> 00:09:35,270
What does the self want?

91
00:09:35,892 --> 00:09:38,134
It just wants to be happy, doesn't it?

92
00:09:38,153 --> 00:09:42,097
I want to be happy, full stop.

93
00:09:42,118 --> 00:09:47,322
So, in order to be happy, it has that feeling, that need to control.

94
00:09:47,383 --> 00:09:54,649
If something painful comes up in the body, it wants to get rid of it, so you take a tablet.

95
00:09:55,529 --> 00:09:58,793
If emotions come up that it doesn't like, it just suppresses it.

96
00:10:00,139 --> 00:10:07,990
And underneath all that, remember, it's always afraid of the body falling sick, the body dying, the body growing old.

97
00:10:09,100 --> 00:10:17,570
So this business of always wanting to live in a pleasant atmosphere, in a happy atmosphere, is, shall we say, the motivation behind the self.

98
00:10:17,590 --> 00:10:27,562
But it's coming from that root misunderstanding that we are this body and this mind and this heart, and the happiness of this body, heart and mind is also dependent on the world.

99
00:10:27,922 --> 00:10:29,224
So good food makes me happy.

100
00:10:29,845 --> 00:10:31,245
So I want to control my food.

101
00:10:31,287 --> 00:10:34,230
I want to be able to cook beautiful things for myself.

102
00:10:39,239 --> 00:10:47,629
So this, of course, the Buddha points out in the second sermon that he gives to these five companions who deserted him because he'd gone a bit soft eating rice pudding.

103
00:10:48,591 --> 00:10:57,743
And he points out, he says, well, if the self were the body, it'd be able to say, be like this, be like that, be able to control it.

104
00:10:58,543 --> 00:11:01,226
He's not talking here about simple movements of lifting something.

105
00:11:01,288 --> 00:11:05,533
He's talking about what we really want, which is not to grow old.

106
00:11:06,273 --> 00:11:10,517
a bit more beautiful, a bit more handsome, and definitely not to die.

107
00:11:11,899 --> 00:11:21,168
So that we have, that wanting to control is, I think, what we mean by free will, the desire for free will.

108
00:11:21,708 --> 00:11:23,591
That's actually what I think we mean at the root of it.

109
00:11:25,273 --> 00:11:30,697
Because, you know, if we're to receive what we desire, then we need to control the source of pleasure.

110
00:11:31,119 --> 00:11:31,779
Full stop.

111
00:11:31,799 --> 00:11:32,279
Simple as that.

112
00:11:34,437 --> 00:11:39,342
Now it's because we fail to do that, in the West anyway, we have these three ideas.

113
00:11:39,984 --> 00:11:43,908
They split into fatalism, libertarianism and determinism.

114
00:11:44,570 --> 00:11:48,534
So you can read all these philosophers and they'll slot into one of these one way or the other.

115
00:11:49,736 --> 00:11:54,142
So fatalism is just that understanding that actually you don't have any free will at all.

116
00:11:54,222 --> 00:11:56,125
In fact the self is utterly impotent.

117
00:11:56,898 --> 00:11:59,241
So acts of free will don't have any effect.

118
00:12:00,124 --> 00:12:02,268
We don't really have any control over our lives.

119
00:12:02,427 --> 00:12:05,293
Anything that happens to us was previously ordained, it's going to happen.

120
00:12:06,495 --> 00:12:15,951
So now if on Thursday I'm driving into Newton Abbott, it doesn't matter if I go fast or slow, whether I take this turn or that turn, if I'm going to have a crash, I'm going to have a crash.

121
00:12:15,971 --> 00:12:16,373
Full stop.

122
00:12:17,214 --> 00:12:18,096
It's bound to happen.

123
00:12:19,442 --> 00:12:22,169
You get this view from people who believe in the stars, don't they?

124
00:12:23,152 --> 00:12:26,721
And then you get that psychology of self-fulfilling prophecy.

125
00:12:27,121 --> 00:12:33,918
So if the stars say, you're bound to fall in love, then they'll find any, a chicken, a horse, whatever, they'll fall in love, you know?

126
00:12:34,278 --> 00:12:35,341
It's got to happen, you know?

127
00:12:39,777 --> 00:12:50,386
And when you think about it, the real important things of our lives, well, it's difficult to say we've got any control at all.

128
00:12:50,706 --> 00:12:52,008
For instance, we didn't choose to be born.

129
00:12:54,429 --> 00:12:56,552
We definitely don't know the hour and day of our death.

130
00:12:57,513 --> 00:12:59,475
We didn't have a choice in cultural conditioning.

131
00:12:59,695 --> 00:13:02,697
What about things like economic, social, cultural?

132
00:13:03,458 --> 00:13:04,399
We just ended up with that.

133
00:13:06,100 --> 00:13:08,062
And then there's the elements, mercy of the elements.

134
00:13:09,798 --> 00:13:13,263
We don't even choose to fall in love, now that I've mentioned it, actually.

135
00:13:16,366 --> 00:13:22,455
And I suppose there's a bit to do, I suppose, with the personality as well.

136
00:13:22,475 --> 00:13:25,698
You know, if you're a fatalist, you know, sort of that hopeless resignation.

137
00:13:26,921 --> 00:13:29,344
If you're that sort of person, you tend to be one, I think.

138
00:13:30,404 --> 00:13:32,548
Or the other side, sanguine optimist or something.

139
00:13:34,570 --> 00:13:41,636
I suppose at best it might build up a sort of stoic patience, a fortitude, you know, a stiff upper lip.

140
00:13:42,998 --> 00:13:43,899
And on with the British.

141
00:13:46,561 --> 00:13:51,085
So this whole idea that we don't have choice, everything's sort of predestined.

142
00:13:51,164 --> 00:13:53,307
I mean, it comes up in the spiritual literature too.

143
00:13:54,168 --> 00:13:57,291
So in terms of the Buddha's day, there was a Makali Gosala.

144
00:13:57,731 --> 00:14:01,455
And all he said was, if you went down one side of the Ganges,

145
00:14:01,434 --> 00:14:28,894
doing great acts of compassion and huge donations and he came up the other side murdering and pillaging it would make a blind bit of difference because the whole road of karma was set every soul that was born would have to go through the whole process of karmic refinement and in his case it did actually lead to some sort of heavenly state but of course it undermines any morality

146
00:14:28,874 --> 00:14:58,273
because it doesn't matter what you do in the end because the universe is so manufactured through samsara that it'll push you to that definite end sort of an absolute fatalism in Christianity you've got Saint Augustine of course he started the one about predestination you know if God knew everything he knew whether you were saved or not and at worst that was Calvinism and Scottish Presbyterianism you're predestined you know

147
00:14:59,687 --> 00:15:03,253
From that there came the Protestant work ethic, of course.

148
00:15:03,273 --> 00:15:16,890
So that even though you couldn't tell whether somebody was going to go to heaven or hell by their earthly deeds, you can understand that one presumed that if you were successful in business, basically you had to go to heaven.

149
00:15:17,192 --> 00:15:24,841
So then you get that work ethic, and people who are rich get to heaven, and people who don't, well, they don't go to heaven.

150
00:15:25,081 --> 00:15:25,763
They go to hell.

151
00:15:26,856 --> 00:15:28,599
Islam is also fatalistic.

152
00:15:28,639 --> 00:15:32,945
It's all written on the tablet, this original tablet.

153
00:15:32,965 --> 00:15:34,386
Your life's written on this tablet.

154
00:15:35,248 --> 00:15:42,557
And there was a lovely case I heard of where a friend of mine was working on an oil rig out in the Middle East.

155
00:15:42,577 --> 00:15:46,722
And two people fell off the rig, two Westerners.

156
00:15:47,264 --> 00:15:50,427
And the current was taking them away, and they were shouting for help.

157
00:15:51,009 --> 00:15:53,471
And there were two soldiers just standing there watching them.

158
00:15:53,941 --> 00:15:58,589
And the manager came rushing down and threw out the lifeboard, pulled it back in.

159
00:15:58,729 --> 00:16:02,033
And he said to these soldiers, he said, you know, why didn't you, why didn't you do that?

160
00:16:02,054 --> 00:16:02,696
Why didn't you help him?

161
00:16:03,336 --> 00:16:04,158
He said, the will of Allah.

162
00:16:07,283 --> 00:16:07,644
Heavy, isn't it?

163
00:16:08,524 --> 00:16:11,831
And in our existentialism, we've got Albert Camus.

164
00:16:12,272 --> 00:16:14,115
You know, he's the one who wrote the myth of Sisyphus.

165
00:16:14,855 --> 00:16:18,581
Now, Sisyphus ended up in hell, if I remember rightly, because of avarice.

166
00:16:19,539 --> 00:16:26,289
And his job, if you remember, was to roll a boulder up a hill, and then, of course, it would go down the other side, so he had to go back down and roll it back up.

167
00:16:26,830 --> 00:16:30,956
And for Camus, that was the metaphor of life.

168
00:16:32,118 --> 00:16:37,245
Every morning, you roll this thing at the top, and overnight it fell back down again.

169
00:16:38,625 --> 00:16:46,134
And when he came to sort of make a judgment about what was the point of having a consciousness which suffered?

170
00:16:46,475 --> 00:16:47,395
What was the point of that?

171
00:16:47,875 --> 00:16:48,937
It's absolutely absurd.

172
00:16:48,976 --> 00:17:00,690
You know, take God away, take any ultimate freedom away, take the idea of salvation or nibbana or liberation away.

173
00:17:01,030 --> 00:17:06,777
What's the point of being conscious when it's such a misery?

174
00:17:06,757 --> 00:17:13,087
So his idea was that a human being, really to maintain his dignity, he only had one choice, which was to commit suicide.

175
00:17:15,131 --> 00:17:17,836
Luckily he was saved, the consequence of his own philosophy.

176
00:17:18,257 --> 00:17:21,883
Died in a car accident.

177
00:17:21,903 --> 00:17:27,593
One wonders whether he'd have carried that one through, actually.

178
00:17:27,752 --> 00:17:31,278
So that's all there's been to fatalism, and definitely the Buddha wasn't into that.

179
00:17:32,525 --> 00:17:34,509
predestination, everything's set.

180
00:17:36,132 --> 00:17:38,455
The opposite of that, of course, is libertarianism.

181
00:17:38,557 --> 00:17:47,934
And that, I think, is, as far as I can remember, the fruit, definitely the fruit of our enlightenment, 18th century enlightenment.

182
00:17:47,954 --> 00:17:55,308
Here, of course, it gets corrupted when a person says they want to do their own thing in their own way in their own time, sort of a teenage rebellion, you know.

183
00:17:56,622 --> 00:17:59,608
But the idea is that we do feel empowered to make choices.

184
00:18:00,471 --> 00:18:05,242
And when you look back, of course, you do see that you have made certain choices.

185
00:18:05,344 --> 00:18:12,842
I mean, you could think that those choices are conditioned, but from a libertarian point of view, there's this bit of rationality come in.

186
00:18:12,821 --> 00:18:18,067
So that things just don't happen, you can stop, you can think about whether this is good or this is bad.

187
00:18:18,547 --> 00:18:27,395
And those decisions, a libertarian would say, are not random, they're not random, and they're not predetermined.

188
00:18:27,996 --> 00:18:31,298
So there's a sense of freedom, a sense of being able to guide one's life.

189
00:18:32,619 --> 00:18:39,707
And you can choose, you see, the idea of choice.

190
00:18:41,797 --> 00:18:44,681
and thereby we affect our decision-making.

191
00:18:45,942 --> 00:19:00,605
So that sort of view went on to support things like individual rights, freedom of speech, freedom of voting, and indeed the capitalist market, because it's the individual now who has to make choices for themselves, and they build up their own wealth.

192
00:19:00,765 --> 00:19:05,711
I mean, that's at its most sort of painful, you might say.

193
00:19:07,767 --> 00:19:12,539
On the other hand, it does make an individual entirely responsible for their actions.

194
00:19:13,000 --> 00:19:18,977
So if a person ends up a robber, you can't sort of suggest mitigating circumstance.

195
00:19:18,997 --> 00:19:20,842
You know, poverty, it's their choice.

196
00:19:20,862 --> 00:19:22,164
It will be a robber, so we'll hang them.

197
00:19:25,891 --> 00:19:28,734
Get on your bike when there's unemployment, you know.

198
00:19:29,336 --> 00:19:32,660
You blame the worker for lack of skills because they've not got jobs and stuff like that.

199
00:19:34,442 --> 00:19:38,448
It leads, doesn't it, to a sort of dog-eat-dog society, if you take it to an extreme.

200
00:19:40,250 --> 00:19:46,278
But the idea of that at a spiritual level, unfortunately from a Buddhist point of view,

201
00:19:46,259 --> 00:20:01,155
It does give the idea of something inside us, this little person, that is a sort of rational self, detached from the world, is able to see things from this vast, indifferent plane, and make sort of decisions about it.

202
00:20:03,940 --> 00:20:07,743
Now, from the Buddha's point of view, that's the source of our misery, actually.

203
00:20:09,309 --> 00:20:20,186
So, I mean, if you, I don't know, if you walk into a supermarket with the idea of buying biscuits, and you're walking down the aisle, you come across a brand you hadn't seen before, Goblet or something.

204
00:20:20,948 --> 00:20:22,691
And you sort of pick it up and it says, Goblet makes you happy.

205
00:20:23,832 --> 00:20:26,896
You look at multi-flavored biscuits, you know.

206
00:20:26,876 --> 00:20:29,883
Then you think, well, in my mind I'm going to buy my favourite figs.

207
00:20:30,845 --> 00:20:32,929
So there you're stuck between a so-called choice.

208
00:20:33,209 --> 00:20:38,519
Well, I mean, you can always say, well, all that's heavily conditioned, but there's some sort of rationality there.

209
00:20:38,960 --> 00:20:39,621
Do I want this?

210
00:20:39,642 --> 00:20:40,082
Do I want that?

211
00:20:40,563 --> 00:20:42,507
Feeling.

212
00:20:42,487 --> 00:20:49,056
See, that's the problem with libertarianism, it sort of lifts choice, it lifts freedom into this idea that it's up in the head somewhere.

213
00:20:49,576 --> 00:21:01,134
But actually you can see, even on a simple thing like choosing a biscuit, or making a vote, making a vote which we call a freedom of vote, but actually it's your feeling, isn't it?

214
00:21:01,153 --> 00:21:03,436
When you see certain politicians, you feel sick.

215
00:21:04,499 --> 00:21:05,759
When you see others, you feel happy.

216
00:21:07,462 --> 00:21:07,583
Right.

217
00:21:11,781 --> 00:21:18,196
So this business of capitalist freedom of choice, I mean, you can definitely argue that it's just juggling with conditioning.

218
00:21:19,932 --> 00:21:23,394
And it's sort of based on this immediate fix, you know.

219
00:21:24,195 --> 00:21:34,664
See, it's very interesting because before the war, if you look at the adverts before the war for products, they were very centered on the product and very pragmatic.

220
00:21:35,266 --> 00:21:37,027
And people only bought what they needed.

221
00:21:37,208 --> 00:21:37,867
That was the idea.

222
00:21:37,887 --> 00:21:38,888
You only bought what you needed.

223
00:21:39,209 --> 00:21:44,173
So if you were selling that in an earlier advert, you would simply point out that it has an alarm.

224
00:21:44,713 --> 00:21:48,037
It's got red lighting so you can see it in the night.

225
00:21:48,518 --> 00:21:49,939
And you'd buy it if you needed it.

226
00:21:49,919 --> 00:21:56,330
If you do it these days, because this was Freud coming through, you've got to put a naked woman next to it.

227
00:21:57,993 --> 00:22:01,519
And the desire that comes up is immediately latched onto the clock so you can't buy it.

228
00:22:03,323 --> 00:22:05,446
It keeps you awake.

229
00:22:07,688 --> 00:22:15,176
So finally, that business of a sort of separate rational self, that won't work in the Buddha's teaching.

230
00:22:16,057 --> 00:22:17,299
Because that's also embedded.

231
00:22:17,820 --> 00:22:21,365
And the third position is this determinism.

232
00:22:22,686 --> 00:22:29,555
So now, here there's the idea that the personal self, that the self does have a choice and it does affect things.

233
00:22:30,476 --> 00:22:31,837
So it's unlike fatalism.

234
00:22:33,119 --> 00:22:37,424
But unlike libertarianism, even the choices you make are determined.

235
00:22:38,266 --> 00:22:40,167
So whatever's going to happen is going to happen.

236
00:22:40,729 --> 00:22:53,585
Now, if you think about that, if everything is just cause and effect, cause and effect, as a sort of sequel from the past, it's very difficult to imagine anything but a repetitive universe.

237
00:22:54,105 --> 00:22:55,567
I mean, where does the newness come in?

238
00:22:56,950 --> 00:23:02,256
Where does something stop this chain of cause and events?

239
00:23:02,676 --> 00:23:06,821
How is it that we have actually a very creative universe?

240
00:23:08,084 --> 00:23:12,048
So it can't be just as simple as a direct historical cause and effect.

241
00:23:13,990 --> 00:23:16,833
The Jains seem to have held that in the Buddhist scriptures.

242
00:23:17,294 --> 00:23:20,076
Now, you've got to be careful here because this is Buddhist propaganda.

243
00:23:22,378 --> 00:23:27,183
There's a man called Upali, for instance, who was a great supporter of the Buddha, a very rich person.

244
00:23:27,884 --> 00:23:36,993
And he told the Jain leader, Naganta, some teaching about what the Buddha had given.

245
00:23:36,973 --> 00:23:41,601
and the Egantha sent him, delegated him to go to the Buddha to prove him wrong.

246
00:23:42,461 --> 00:23:46,428
So, of course, Upali gets up to the Buddha there and starts his discussion.

247
00:23:46,728 --> 00:23:50,532
And by the end of it, he becomes a follower of the Buddha, you see.

248
00:23:50,594 --> 00:23:52,435
So, he wants to become a follower.

249
00:23:52,476 --> 00:23:54,459
He says, you know, and I shall leave the Egantha.

250
00:23:54,598 --> 00:23:59,286
This is where the Buddha's magnanimity, one of the little examples of his magnanimity, is, well, don't.

251
00:23:59,266 --> 00:24:02,250
Don't stop supporting your other teacher.

252
00:24:02,310 --> 00:24:04,894
You can support me, but don't stop supporting him, you see.

253
00:24:04,914 --> 00:24:08,540
Anyway, Upali returns back to the Naganth and tells him that he's now been converted.

254
00:24:09,241 --> 00:24:14,210
And the Naganth, it seems, is so angry that he spews blood and dies.

255
00:24:15,090 --> 00:24:23,684
So it's that sort of tale which makes you think, well, when they're talking about Jains, maybe it's a bit of propaganda, you know.

256
00:24:23,704 --> 00:24:26,269
I think he died in the Jain way, starving himself to death.

257
00:24:28,020 --> 00:24:35,111
And what the Buddha points out about the Jain theory, which was some idea of predestination, you had to stop.

258
00:24:35,251 --> 00:24:36,192
You had to stop doing.

259
00:24:36,534 --> 00:24:39,176
So you stopped killing, and eventually you stopped eating.

260
00:24:39,678 --> 00:24:42,102
The idea was just to draw karma to an end.

261
00:24:42,843 --> 00:24:45,547
So the Buddhist saint actually dies of starvation.

262
00:24:46,387 --> 00:24:48,310
You sort of build up your courage for it, I suppose.

263
00:24:49,653 --> 00:24:52,897
What the Buddha points out is that even that decision is part of karma.

264
00:24:53,397 --> 00:24:57,825
That actually won't end the sequence of cause and effect.

265
00:24:57,805 --> 00:25:00,468
It's like when we don't do something has an effect.

266
00:25:06,854 --> 00:25:15,241
Even if you take this gathering now, you see, we've all come from different paths to create this particular situation.

267
00:25:17,083 --> 00:25:20,547
And in this situation, hopefully something creative is happening.

268
00:25:21,907 --> 00:25:25,010
Only because we've all come here from different places.

269
00:25:25,682 --> 00:25:37,583
So there is something about the way the universe works which is about different lines of cause and effect meeting at a certain point to create something new.

270
00:25:40,144 --> 00:25:55,570
So we see that these three perspectives, fatalism, determinism, libertarianism, I think we might argue that if you look back in time, you might just get the feeling that everything has been predetermined.

271
00:25:56,472 --> 00:26:02,102
Your life's actually been fairly set, and you didn't have much of a choice, and you've ended up where you are because...

272
00:26:02,807 --> 00:26:09,297
But when you're actually stuck in a present dilemma, when you're actually stuck between this and that, it definitely feels like you've got a choice.

273
00:26:10,439 --> 00:26:12,020
So again, it's to do with feeling.

274
00:26:12,040 --> 00:26:18,269
It's to do with the way we're looking at something as to which side of this business you tend to fall on.

275
00:26:19,491 --> 00:26:24,057
Anyway, you might be relieved to know that from the Buddha's point of view, we're simply asking the wrong question.

276
00:26:24,900 --> 00:26:29,405
So you can now forget the first part of this particular essay, right?

277
00:26:31,781 --> 00:26:42,096
Because this whole business of free will just arises out of this profound delusion beneath us, you know, it's a sort of nebulous idea of me, me in control, you see.

278
00:26:42,696 --> 00:26:51,289
So as the self discovers the world, there's pleasant, unpleasant experiences, so it wants to create something out of it, this dualistic world.

279
00:26:51,349 --> 00:26:56,457
So all things are over there as rivals or this side as accomplices.

280
00:26:57,567 --> 00:27:02,314
It's just driven by greed, aversion, indulging, accumulating, rejecting, annihilating.

281
00:27:02,835 --> 00:27:06,520
And it's this way that the self gains this idea of power.

282
00:27:07,422 --> 00:27:08,983
It's just a little game it's playing.

283
00:27:10,326 --> 00:27:13,411
So obviously the right question is, how do we put an end to suffering?

284
00:27:14,353 --> 00:27:20,382
Remember that the Buddha always reduced his teaching to a very simple statement, suffering and the end of suffering, full stop.

285
00:27:20,942 --> 00:27:23,727
So the question is, how do we end suffering?

286
00:27:23,707 --> 00:27:27,231
And how do you get down to really cut the root?

287
00:27:27,792 --> 00:27:31,258
The first thing is to understand this business about conditionality.

288
00:27:32,220 --> 00:27:45,259
And as we've already said, it's a concurrence of past events meeting present situations, which allows us this feeling of creativity, something new all the time.

289
00:27:47,990 --> 00:27:54,157
Secondly, the aim is not concerned with freedom of choice at all.

290
00:27:54,377 --> 00:27:56,882
The aim to end suffering is not to do with choice at all.

291
00:27:57,342 --> 00:27:58,443
It's to do with clarity.

292
00:27:58,463 --> 00:28:00,987
It's to do with seeing where the path is.

293
00:28:01,007 --> 00:28:10,960
It's to do with investigation and exploration of our lives and the way things are and how it is that we keep falling into suffering.

294
00:28:12,339 --> 00:28:19,008
If you, like for instance, if we set out for a walk in the country, you've already decided where you want to go.

295
00:28:20,108 --> 00:28:21,049
It's not sort of random.

296
00:28:21,089 --> 00:28:22,211
You've decided where you want to go.

297
00:28:22,751 --> 00:28:24,094
So in our sense, you want to be happy.

298
00:28:24,233 --> 00:28:25,655
You want to find this happiness.

299
00:28:25,675 --> 00:28:26,477
And you've got your map.

300
00:28:26,497 --> 00:28:27,577
You've got your compass, you see.

301
00:28:27,837 --> 00:28:33,084
When you come to a fork in the road, you don't choose, well, shall I go down this one or shall I go down that one?

302
00:28:33,124 --> 00:28:34,506
You already know where you're going to go.

303
00:28:34,546 --> 00:28:38,871
And all you've got to do is consult the map and make the right decision.

304
00:28:40,116 --> 00:28:44,344
So in the Buddha's path, the path is already delineated.

305
00:28:45,144 --> 00:28:49,712
So this choice, this feeling of choice that we have, turns out to be nothing but a doubt.

306
00:28:50,815 --> 00:28:56,423
It's not actually... See, the self lifts it up to the idea of, well, shall I do this or shall I do that?

307
00:28:56,784 --> 00:29:00,150
But actually, if you know all the facts, you wouldn't have a choice.

308
00:29:01,025 --> 00:29:02,987
The path would be just directly in front of you.

309
00:29:03,968 --> 00:29:05,230
Spiritually speaking, especially.

310
00:29:06,451 --> 00:29:08,772
So, there's two types of...

311
00:29:08,792 --> 00:29:10,535
When I say doubt, there's two types here.

312
00:29:10,555 --> 00:29:15,240
There's what you might call honest doubt and sceptical doubt.

313
00:29:15,260 --> 00:29:19,005
So, honest doubt is just coming from that business of not knowing.

314
00:29:19,545 --> 00:29:25,010
And it comes from, shall we say, a sense of a grounded humility.

315
00:29:25,230 --> 00:29:26,512
You know, like, I don't know.

316
00:29:26,532 --> 00:29:27,993
I really don't know.

317
00:29:28,055 --> 00:29:30,356
Sort of accepting that.

318
00:29:30,336 --> 00:29:32,200
And it's a very difficult place to be, isn't it?

319
00:29:32,740 --> 00:29:33,501
We like to know.

320
00:29:33,521 --> 00:29:40,413
That not knowing can cause us extreme sort of anxiety.

321
00:29:40,593 --> 00:29:42,916
Like you don't know whether you're going to have the job next week.

322
00:29:43,297 --> 00:29:45,039
You don't know whether the check's going to come.

323
00:29:45,059 --> 00:29:47,063
It creates anxiety.

324
00:29:47,042 --> 00:29:58,757
But if we can sit patiently, if we can sit calmly within that not knowing and accept that state and then just keep looking, keep observing, then the path manifests.

325
00:29:58,777 --> 00:30:05,084
It either manifests because somebody's pointed it out to us or because our own experience manifests.

326
00:30:05,104 --> 00:30:14,535
One of the points in the process of these vipassana jnana, the vipassana understandings, is the business of what is the path and what is not the path.

327
00:30:14,515 --> 00:30:21,969
And it's a very simple thing, most of you have probably been there, is that in your meditation you'll suddenly start maybe getting these beautiful states.

328
00:30:22,529 --> 00:30:25,717
They're very peaceful, very spaced out, very lovely and joyful.

329
00:30:26,438 --> 00:30:31,106
And of course there's the self immediately wants to get in there and say, well this is it, finally I made it.

330
00:30:31,086 --> 00:30:40,557
I remember one man told me he had this, quite deluded really, he had this amazing experience while sitting on the toilet.

331
00:30:41,138 --> 00:30:42,519
Now that's not relevant.

332
00:30:42,579 --> 00:30:44,201
You can have these amazing experiences anywhere.

333
00:30:44,883 --> 00:30:50,390
Remember that Luther had his great breakthrough while he was sitting on the toilet.

334
00:30:50,410 --> 00:30:51,150
It's faith only.

335
00:30:52,211 --> 00:30:53,313
But he absolutely insisted.

336
00:30:53,373 --> 00:30:53,993
He was a Nibbana.

337
00:30:54,755 --> 00:30:56,757
And just what he was describing was just amazing.

338
00:30:57,242 --> 00:30:58,704
You know, just a blissful state, really.

339
00:30:59,325 --> 00:31:03,048
So, knowing that whatever nibbana is, it is not felt.

340
00:31:03,650 --> 00:31:05,971
Whatever nibbana is, it is not an emotional state.

341
00:31:06,291 --> 00:31:08,454
Whatever nibbana is, it cannot be described.

342
00:31:09,015 --> 00:31:12,018
Immediately, it takes you off that indulgence.

343
00:31:12,919 --> 00:31:13,519
See?

344
00:31:13,539 --> 00:31:14,361
That's a correction.

345
00:31:14,980 --> 00:31:22,709
That's a correction to that not knowing, that doubt which comes up from, shall we say, this desire to seek the end of suffering.

346
00:31:23,230 --> 00:31:24,050
That's a wisdom thing.

347
00:31:24,070 --> 00:31:26,153
That's coming from something deeper than the self.

348
00:31:27,365 --> 00:31:51,938
When you get the doubt which is really a sceptical doubt, a doubt which is a mental illness in the same way that sloth and torpor and all these addictions are, then of course there's something else going on there, and that's usually a fear of commitment, usually a fear of sort of giving yourself to something because you don't know what's going to happen, but that fear stops you committing and therefore stops you meditating.

349
00:31:53,487 --> 00:32:06,538
one of the people who used to organise the doubling group, his father, when he was a young child, you know, put him on a table and opened up his arms and said, jump, son, see, and he jumped and he moved away.

350
00:32:07,220 --> 00:32:09,902
Splat on the ground, he said.

351
00:32:10,403 --> 00:32:11,723
And he says, that'll teach you.

352
00:32:12,084 --> 00:32:13,204
See, don't trust anybody.

353
00:32:14,026 --> 00:32:16,307
You can imagine, yeah?

354
00:32:16,327 --> 00:32:22,953
So, I mean, when they come to the Buddha's teaching, it was quite amazing that he should actually, you know, put his heart and soul into it.

355
00:32:23,305 --> 00:32:31,217
So, just to be aware of that, that the path isn't about, shall I do this or shall I do that?

356
00:32:31,477 --> 00:32:33,921
And that's one reason for a schedule, you see.

357
00:32:34,602 --> 00:32:39,548
You set your schedule down, a schedule that you know you can follow, and you just do that religiously.

358
00:32:39,648 --> 00:32:42,073
You don't let this little self come in and say,

359
00:32:42,053 --> 00:32:43,075
Well, shall I do it?

360
00:32:43,315 --> 00:32:43,796
Can't do it?

361
00:32:43,816 --> 00:32:44,717
Maybe a little kip.

362
00:32:45,518 --> 00:32:46,239
I'll go for a walk.

363
00:32:46,720 --> 00:32:47,461
Don't feel like it.

364
00:32:47,761 --> 00:32:48,142
See?

365
00:32:48,162 --> 00:32:50,766
And all the time you're just feeding the self.

366
00:32:51,487 --> 00:32:57,797
When it comes to joining the order, you say, look, I don't get up in the morning and say, shall I wear blue?

367
00:32:58,577 --> 00:32:59,759
It doesn't occur.

368
00:33:00,942 --> 00:33:02,084
Even the idea of what shall I eat?

369
00:33:02,625 --> 00:33:03,605
What am I going to eat?

370
00:33:04,227 --> 00:33:09,492
So it's sort of taking out all that sort of edge around where the self can sort of manifest.

371
00:33:09,512 --> 00:33:19,986
It doesn't mean to say it doesn't manifest in very peculiar and staged ways, but at least one sort of, you know, you try and draw a circle around, you know, like what you can do, what you can't do.

372
00:33:20,567 --> 00:33:22,229
And then you liberate.

373
00:33:22,409 --> 00:33:24,050
See, that's the benefit.

374
00:33:24,070 --> 00:33:30,858
You then liberate this wisdom factor, this panya, this intuitive intelligence to investigate.

375
00:33:30,838 --> 00:33:36,586
If this intuitive intelligence gets locked into what the self wants to do, then it's just taken all over the place.

376
00:33:36,867 --> 00:33:42,015
Fine, you feel nice when you get out for a walk, but I mean, you know, has it helped you overcome suffering?

377
00:33:42,035 --> 00:33:42,496
Not at all.

378
00:33:42,675 --> 00:33:45,420
All it's done is it's given you a greater addiction to walking the countryside.

379
00:33:47,083 --> 00:33:48,904
Just deepening your attachment to the country.

380
00:33:51,388 --> 00:33:53,612
Which I've learnt since coming down to Devon, by the way.

381
00:33:54,794 --> 00:33:55,153
Terrible.

382
00:33:57,617 --> 00:33:58,398
So...

383
00:34:01,315 --> 00:34:04,960
We could almost say, if you really think about it, when have you been most happy?

384
00:34:06,501 --> 00:34:09,326
Isn't it when you've been doing exactly what you wanted to do?

385
00:34:11,007 --> 00:34:12,550
I mean, the actual doing of it.

386
00:34:14,293 --> 00:34:15,393
It's never occurred, has it?

387
00:34:15,414 --> 00:34:19,559
When you've been doing exactly what you wanted to do, it's never occurred, shall I do this or shall I not do that?

388
00:34:22,384 --> 00:34:24,626
And it's the same with interest.

389
00:34:24,766 --> 00:34:28,992
If you notice, whenever you're interested in something, do you ever have any problems with concentration?

390
00:34:30,434 --> 00:34:30,494
No.

391
00:34:30,813 --> 00:34:37,452
So a lot of our practice is giving up that sort of choice, is raising the interest to discover the path.

392
00:34:37,472 --> 00:34:44,856
And all that stuff just follows naturally, the clarity and all that, and the energy and the concentration.

393
00:34:47,197 --> 00:34:51,684
Now when it comes to will itself, there is will, there is will in terms of power.

394
00:34:52,905 --> 00:34:54,527
The Buddha equates that to action.

395
00:34:55,268 --> 00:34:56,630
So he states it quite clearly.

396
00:34:57,190 --> 00:34:58,452
Will I call action.

397
00:34:59,074 --> 00:35:05,663
So those of you who know the Wheel of Dependent Origination, there comes that point, so we say it starts off with that contact we talked about.

398
00:35:06,182 --> 00:35:10,208
It starts off with a perception feeling of being pleasant, unpleasant.

399
00:35:10,809 --> 00:35:13,572
It would then have that reaction of wanting, not wanting.

400
00:35:13,713 --> 00:35:14,934
That's your tanha.

401
00:35:14,954 --> 00:35:17,137
Only then does this self come in.

402
00:35:17,117 --> 00:35:19,900
Which is very interesting because in language we say, I want that.

403
00:35:20,101 --> 00:35:22,202
But actually it's, that want I.

404
00:35:22,222 --> 00:35:26,686
That's how it happens in terms of psychology.

405
00:35:27,007 --> 00:35:30,630
As soon as that I comes in, you can't stop it, you've empowered it.

406
00:35:30,650 --> 00:35:39,699
As soon as that I says, I want, then you get that empowerment, that's the will coming in, and you have that next link, bhava, which is becoming.

407
00:35:40,340 --> 00:35:41,701
That's when you become, that's your act.

408
00:35:42,101 --> 00:35:43,782
Act of thought, word or deed.

409
00:35:44,657 --> 00:35:56,673
So that's why in your meditation, when it comes to things like pleasant, unpleasant, you just want to keep the mind very close to that business of wanting, not wanting, liking, not liking, wanting, not wanting.

410
00:35:57,655 --> 00:36:07,728
And that's the way out to liberation by understanding dukkha, by understanding suffering and satisfactoriness.

411
00:36:07,748 --> 00:36:12,454
So this power that we have is quite mysterious.

412
00:36:12,652 --> 00:36:13,675
It's totally neutral.

413
00:36:13,835 --> 00:36:15,338
It's not good or bad.

414
00:36:15,398 --> 00:36:16,340
It depends how you use it.

415
00:36:16,360 --> 00:36:17,563
It depends on your attitude.

416
00:36:18,063 --> 00:36:19,746
And you can't separate it from the action.

417
00:36:22,030 --> 00:36:22,552
You can try.

418
00:36:22,612 --> 00:36:24,677
When you do walking meditation, just stand there.

419
00:36:24,737 --> 00:36:27,001
Keep saying, intending to walk.

420
00:36:27,021 --> 00:36:28,224
Intending to walk.

421
00:36:28,905 --> 00:36:32,291
And even though you're saying it and intending it, nothing's going to happen.

422
00:36:33,112 --> 00:36:34,476
And then suddenly the foot lifts.

423
00:36:35,907 --> 00:36:39,914
So what is it that has taken something out of a potential into an actual?

424
00:36:40,614 --> 00:36:41,918
That's what the Buddha's calling will.

425
00:36:42,619 --> 00:36:44,583
And you can't separate it from your foot.

426
00:36:44,603 --> 00:36:47,628
You can't say, well, that's it over here, and this is my foot over here.

427
00:36:48,108 --> 00:36:49,010
It's one and the same thing.

428
00:36:49,490 --> 00:36:52,617
It's within the structure of this whole becoming business.

429
00:36:54,233 --> 00:36:56,496
But the power of that will is your conditioning.

430
00:36:56,615 --> 00:37:01,423
So remember, an action forms an intention, moves you to an action.

431
00:37:02,224 --> 00:37:06,371
And if that action is wholesome or unwholesome, then you're going to get the product of that conditioning.

432
00:37:06,650 --> 00:37:10,617
So if it's an unwholesome action, it moves you towards an unwholesome conditioning.

433
00:37:10,998 --> 00:37:11,798
This is inwardly, yeah?

434
00:37:12,820 --> 00:37:15,123
Remember, all karma in terms of liberation is inward.

435
00:37:15,164 --> 00:37:17,507
It's not something to do with the outside world at all, actually.

436
00:37:17,891 --> 00:37:25,003
And anything you do which is wholesome, it will produce that wholesome conditioning within you.

437
00:37:25,864 --> 00:37:29,050
And in Buddhist understanding, that's what's driving us to a particular destiny.

438
00:37:34,378 --> 00:37:37,824
And that's why, of course, in the Noble Eightfold Path, right view heads it.

439
00:37:38,952 --> 00:37:46,942
As soon as you understand, as soon as there's a seeing, as soon as there's a perception of the way things are, this immediately informs your attitude.

440
00:37:47,362 --> 00:37:51,847
Of course, when it gets down into the attitude, you may find the opposite attitude to be too strong.

441
00:37:52,248 --> 00:37:58,396
So you might go down and you very clearly perceive that the body does not need tea.

442
00:37:59,237 --> 00:38:03,541
But that's not going to stop you doing it because of this huge conditioning to drink tea.

443
00:38:03,521 --> 00:38:21,699
but at least there's the perception that at this present time the body doesn't actually need tea and it's hanging on to that and waiting for that to drop into the heart as an attitude and then it balances up with the desire to have tea and eventually because you're not

444
00:38:21,679 --> 00:38:48,666
feeding the desire to have tea anymore that drops away and the right attitude of seeing food and water and all that as nourishment for the body not as a place for seeking happiness begins to get the upper hand and lead you to the enlightenment that's the one I'm struggling with so that's that's called Dhamma Chaitanya the will for Dhamma and that translates into Mahayana as the Bodhicitta the heart seeking enlightenment

445
00:38:50,485 --> 00:38:52,570
So eventually, that's the force.

446
00:38:53,050 --> 00:38:56,018
That's the force behind your drive to liberation.

447
00:38:58,664 --> 00:39:07,565
And just finally, to end off with this lovely refrain, when anybody gets liberated, you always get this little refrain at the end of it.

448
00:39:07,545 --> 00:39:09,027
Birth is destroyed.

449
00:39:09,248 --> 00:39:11,132
Now, this is the birth of self, remember.

450
00:39:12,434 --> 00:39:13,976
The holy life has been lived.

451
00:39:14,938 --> 00:39:17,782
What had to be done has been done.

452
00:39:17,802 --> 00:39:22,550
There is no more coming into any state of self-existence.

453
00:39:24,067 --> 00:39:25,208
Can you feel the relief in that?

454
00:39:25,568 --> 00:39:28,391
What had to be done has been done.

455
00:39:29,753 --> 00:39:34,878
So it's a case really of being clear that the path to enlightenment isn't a choice.

456
00:39:35,438 --> 00:39:36,820
It's not a choice.

457
00:39:36,840 --> 00:39:37,601
It's a discovery.

458
00:39:38,101 --> 00:39:43,628
What leads us to it is the general dissatisfaction about our lives.

459
00:39:44,528 --> 00:39:50,315
And once you perceive which way to go, then it's a case of building up that courage, that determination, resolution to follow it.

460
00:39:50,815 --> 00:39:52,436
And then, of course, you get the benefit of it.

461
00:39:53,563 --> 00:39:54,467
That's the answer.

462
00:39:54,806 --> 00:39:56,070
That's what we have to do.

463
00:39:56,311 --> 00:39:57,956
So, what's the message?

464
00:39:58,376 --> 00:39:59,701
Abandon free will.

465
00:40:02,409 --> 00:40:03,190
Devote yourself.

466
00:40:03,431 --> 00:40:07,181
Surrender to the path.

467
00:40:07,202 --> 00:40:12,637
May these words have been of awesome help to you in your path to liberation.

468
00:40:13,699 --> 00:40:14,442
Thank you very much.

